VCruising along melodic scales
p3
sVnews
p4
VSanhita Nandi presented a Hindustani vocal concert as part of the Parampara Festival. She chose raga Madhuvanti in vilambit ektaal for the lyric &#8216;Re Kaise Jayoon Sakhi,' embellishing her gayaki with beautiful swaras and phrases. The meend and the glides in the final variations were sung straight from the soul.This was followed by a piece in dhrut, &#8216;More Dar Laage Sundar Salone Sanwariya.' Sanhita's elaboration of the raga was so deftly done that every facet unfolded in a smooth manner.Endowed with a cultured voice, Sanhita brought out murkis, and her singing of kaan swaras seemed effortless. There was Phirat in her sargams and her swift taans were electrifying.Kirana gharanaSanhita showcased the Kirana Gharana by exploring every phrase. There was spontaneity in her singing that led to its own movement. Her rendition had energy, and momentum. In raga Megh, Sanhita presented &#8216;Aari Sakhi' in vilambit, &#8216;Badal Garje Chamkat damini' in Madhya and &#8216;Barkha Ritu Aaye Sanwariya' in dhrut. Concentrating on the profundity and majesty of the raga, the singer developed it with &#233;lan, exploring various scales.Guru Nanak's bhajan in Chaurkesi stood out for its purity that evoked the feeling of surrender and bhakti. Rajendra Nakod on the tabla and Umakant Puranik on the harmonium were instrumental in exploring fresh patterns in raga and laya.
